  • summary of pre-processing. Looks like samples have not been blank corrected, but Petr has confirmed.

Step 3. First PARAFAC attempt. Lower “resolution”

Aim: obtain the correct number of components

 #10) First attempt PARAFAC model
# minimum and maximum of numbers of components
# parameter settings from stardom guideline
cores <- detectCores(logical = FALSE)
dim_min <- 2
dim_max <- 4

nstart <- 25 # number of similar models from which best is chosen
maxit = 5000 # maximum number of iterations in PARAFAC analysis
ctol <- 10^-6 # tolerance in PARAFAC analysis

# 11) calculating PARAFAC models, one for each number of components
#using non-negative constraints
pf1 <- eem_parafac(eem_list2, comps = seq(dim_min,dim_max), normalise = FALSE, const = c("nonneg", "nonneg", "nonneg"), maxit = maxit, nstart = nstart, ctol = ctol, cores = cores)

# 12) rescale B and C modes to a maximum fluorescence of 1 for each component
pf1n <- lapply(pf1, eempf_rescaleBC, newscale = "Fmax")
#Compare the different models in plot
eempf_compare(pf1n, contour = TRUE)

- the fit of the models is good (r2), very small increase going from 3 to 4 components - the excitation and emission bands do not look perfect, worsen for every added component - strong correlation between the components. Therefore, data is normalised. Doesnt help a lot though. - Interestingly, the third component looks identical to 1000Lakes assumed contamination

Step 4. Evaluate extreme samples/wavelengths

Step 6. Created model is exported to OpenFluor to compare with other studies and identify the components

From OpenFluor the following can be linked to the model components: C1: Humic-material, larger-sized, characteristic of soil, sediment and freshwater environments, recalcitrant soil or plant material, highly resistant to microbial degradation but suspictible to photodecay (https://doi.org/10.1016/j.geoderma.2017.06.029), similar to soil-fulvic material (10.1080/00785236.2003.10409512) C2: Humic-material, mid-sized, characteristic of soil, sediment and freshwater environments, recalcitrant soil or plant material, highly resistant to microbial degradation but suspictible to photodecay (https://doi.org/10.1016/j.geoderma.2017.06.029) C3: protein-like material (tryptophane/tyrosine), often linked to anthropogenic disctrubances (10.1890/12-0825.1)
